Scope of the Reference Implementation

This release includes:

structural coordinate admissibility definitions
coordinate visibility rules
minimal executable reference
deterministic certificates
visual coordinate outputs
reference traces

S-Coordinate defines a deterministic structural model where coordinate visibility emerges from structure:

resolve(structure) ->

VISIBLE if structure is complete AND consistent
NOT_VISIBLE if structure is incomplete
NOT_VISIBLE if structure is inconsistent

What This Demonstrates
coordinate admissibility without blind spatial assumption
independence from rendering as a source of truth
independence from GPS trust as a prerequisite for admissibility
independence from map-layer trust
structural resolution governing coordinate visibility
safe handling of incomplete and conflicting structure
deterministic and reproducible visibility states
identical structure produces identical visibility and certificate
Conformance

An implementation is considered compatible if it preserves:

structure-based coordinate admissibility
independence from blind spatial assumption
deterministic resolution
structure-driven coordinate visibility
reproducibility of visibility and certificate under equivalent inputs
explicit handling of incomplete and conflicting structure

Conformance is judged solely by observable behavior — not by internal implementation.

S1 = S2 -> Visibility1 = Visibility2 -> Certificate1 = Certificate2

Conflict Handling

In this reference implementation:

NOT_VISIBLE is explicitly defined and demonstrated
incomplete structure produces no visible coordinate
inconsistent conditions do not produce admissible visibility

Conformance requires:

no forced visibility under incomplete structure
no arbitrary visibility under conflicting structure
Normalization Requirement

For deterministic certificate identity:

normalized_visibility = normalize(Visibility)

certificate = hash(normalized_visibility)

Normalization ensures:

independence from rendering state
independence from representation format
consistent certificate identity across systems and runs

In the reference implementation:

SHA-256 (truncated) is used for demonstration.

Dependency Independence Guarantee

Coordinate admissibility is invariant under dependency state:

resolve(S, D1) = resolve(S, D2) for all dependency states D1, D2

This ensures:

dependency_failure != admissibility_failure

Coordinate admissibility depends only on structure — not rendering or infrastructure state.

Relationship to Shunyaya Framework

S-Coordinate is part of the broader Shunyaya framework.

It builds on:

SLANG → correctness without execution
ORL → correctness without ordering
STIME → correctness without time
STINT → correctness without connectivity
STILE → correctness without communication
SVARE → correctness without computation
STIC → correctness without cloud dependency
STRUMER → media without editing
S-Coordinate → coordinate visibility without blind spatial assumption

Each removes a dependency.

Admissibility remains preserved by structure.

